my, human physiology, and mental illness, the new diagnosis founded the medical conviction and popular belief that habitual drinking could become a psychological and physiological disease. By midcentury, delirium tremens had inspired a wide range of popular theater, poetry, fiction, and illustration. This romantic fascination endured into the twentieth century, most notably in the classic Disney cartoon Dumbo, in which a pink pachyderm marching band haunts a drunken young elephant. Rum Maniacs reveals just how delirium tremens shaped the modern experience of alcohol addiction as a psychic struggle with inner demons.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDelirium tremensxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aDelirium tremenszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aDelirium tremenszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aDelirium tremenszUnited StatesxPsychological aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 0aSocial ecology. 0aTemperancezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022609989740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226099927423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226099927/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles